Hybrid-parallel algorithms for 2D Green‚Äôs functions
Alejandro √Ålvarez-Melc√≥na , Domingo Gim√©nezb,1 , Fernando D. Quesadaa , Tom√°s
Ram√≠rezb
a Departamento

de Tecnolog√≠as de la Informaci√≥n y las Comunicaciones, Polytechnic University of Cartagena, Spain
b Departamento de Inform√°tica y Sistemas, University of Murcia, Spain

Abstract
Green‚Äôs functions are used to solve non homogeneous integral equations with boundary conditions. In electromagnetism
they are used for a large class of problems, including the analysis of microwave circuits, antennas, and the investigation of
breakdown phenomena in microwave transmission lines. In many cases it is necessary to compute a large number of Green‚Äôs
functions between pairs of source and observation points. Today, basic computational systems are composed of multiple
CPUs (multicores) and GPUs, and it is necessary to adapt the software used for the solution of scientiÔ¨Åc problems to these
systems. This paper studies the optimization of the computation of 2D rectangular waveguide Green‚Äôs functions in clusters
of multicores with GPUs. Different basic algorithms are considered, and the most efÔ¨Åcient implementations are obtained by
adequately combining basic algorithms in hybrid parallelism programs.
Keywords: Green‚Äôs functions, Hybrid Parallel Computing, Performance Estimation, Clusters, Multicore, Multi-GPU

1. Introduction
Integral and differential equations are mathematical tools with applications in a variety of scientiÔ¨Åc problems.
There are several methods to solve them: variables separation, Fourier series, method of moments, etc., [1]. Some
methods are based on Green‚Äôs functions [2], which are used to formulate non homogeneous integral equations
subject to boundary conditions. They are used in different Ô¨Åelds, and this paper focuses on Green‚Äôs functions
inside rectangular waveguides [3], which are used in the analysis and design of microwave circuits, especially
for high power applications. These functions can be expressed in the form of inÔ¨Ånite series in spatial or spectral
domains. They present some computational problems due to slow convergence of these series.
When solving practical problems, the need to calculate hundreds or thousands of Green‚Äôs functions generates
a high computational cost, and methods to accelerate the convergence of the series and to reduce the execution
time are necessary. With the Ewald‚Äôs method only a reduced number of terms in the series is calculated, and the
convergence speed increases [4]. This method exploits the extraction of electrostatic interactions, and involves
the calculation of both short and long spectral range interactions. Following this technique, the calculation can be
represented in the real space as the sum of two terms:
de f

œÜ (r) ‚áíœÜ sr (r) + œÜlr (r)
